<DOCNO> XIE19990103.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese New Leaders Committed to Policy Shift </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 2 (Xinhua) -- With a pragmatic Salim Hoss
having replaced an ambitious Rafik Hariri as prime minister,
Lebanese are undergoing a major shift in the government policy
from huge expenses to financial austerities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Emile Lahoud, sworn in as Lebanese president only
about two months ago to replace his predecessor Elias Hrawi, has
vowed to fight corruption rampancy amid mounting public calls for
a clean government and politics.
</P>
<P>
In a policy statement approved by the parliament on December
17, Hoss said a major challenge facing his government is how to
halt the financial drain caused by past policies such as the
reconstruction policy.
</P>
<P>
Hoss said the new government will strive to tame huge public
debts and budget deficits by pursuing "austerity in the extreme,"
and will stop borrowing from abroad in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to rebuild the country from the devastation of the
1975-90 civil war, the former prime minister Hariri had been
pushing forward a multibillion dollar reconstruction program since
he came to power in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Hariri's government borrowed heavily from local banks and on the
international market to finance huge infrastructure projects in
road, telecommunication, water and electricity.
</P>
<P>
The projects, despite being necessary to attract investment in
a postwar Lebanon, resulted in a staggering public debt of about
18 billion U.S. dollars by the end of 1998 and an annual budget
deficit of more than 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Hariri government issued 1.45 billion dollars of Euro
bonds on international market, adding one more heavy financial
burden on the new administration.
</P>
<P>
However, Hoss has pledged that signed contracts will be honored
though his government is being confronted with financial
difficulties. But he said priorities will only be given to those
that do not exceed the financial capabilities of the state.
</P>
<P>
Any new project will be subjected to careful study before it is
carried out, and some non-urgent ones will be shelved, the new
prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Besides taking measures to tighten the nation's purse strings,
Hoss has also planned to explore ways to increase revenues.
</P>
<P>
He said privatization will be cautiously introduced in certain
public sectors to ensure receipts from non-productive state-run
ventures such as the ailing Middle East Airlines, Lebanon's
national carrier, the cash-strapped state TV station Tele Liban
and the Casino du Liban, the biggest gaming house in the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
In addition, tax collection, the main source for the country's
coffers, will be intensified. It is reported that only 55 percent
of the country's 4 million population paid their electricity bills
and taxes in 1997.
</P>
<P>
As an economist, Hoss appointed many fresh faces and a number
of specialists to his cabinet to seek pragmatic solutions to the
problems of the country. "This government will inspire great
confidence and reassure people. It augurs well," Hoss said.
</P>
<P>
The deep-rooted corruption has long been considered a hallmark
of Lebanese politics. Many officials in Hariri's administration
were reportedly involved in taking bribes and squandering public
funds.
</P>
<P>
Hariri, who amassed nearly 3 billion dollars of fortune in
Saudi Arabia, was also accused by opponents of increasing his
wealth through country's reconstruction projects.
</P>
<P>
The newly elected president Lahoud, a former army commander and
well-known for honesty, hard working and success in rebuilding a
non-sectarian army, has demonstrated his resolution to eliminate
corruption in the country.
</P>
<P>
"No one is allowed to be above the law and I will be under the
law," Lahoud said in his inaugural speech October 24.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud's speeches, rekindling the hope of disappointed
Lebanese, met with warm welcome and praises from various political
and religious factions.
</P>
<P>
For sure, there must be many unexpected obstacles ahead as Hoss
admitted, but most Lebanese believe that as long as their country
is run in the hands of honest leaders with realistic measures, it
will take off in a positive and bright direction.
</P>
<P>
"The year 1998 was a turning point in our history," said Sami
Sfeir, senior official at Lebanese Central Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
