<HEADLINE> Clinton Asks Congress for Big Military Spending Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
announced Saturday that he would propose an increase of over 12
billion dollars in U.S. defense spending in his upcoming budget.
</P>
<P>
"The budget I will submit to Congress... will provide an
increase of over 12 billion dollars for defense readiness and
modernization," Clinton said in his weekly radio address.
</P>
<P>
The proposal for an overall six-year increase of 100 billion
dollars, if approved by congressional appropriators, would be the
first increase in Pentagon spending above inflation since 1991,
the year of the Persian Gulf War, and the largest since the Cold
War buildup of the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
"We must undertake this effort today so that our nation will
remain strong and secure tomorrow," Clinton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
