<HEADLINE> 010203   S. Africa Not to Send Troops to Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 2 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has not been
requested to send troops to Angola and remains committed to the U.N.
diplomatic initiatives in the war-torn country, South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki's spokesman said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Rumors that South Africa was going to send troops to help quell the
renewed civil war in Angola were untrue, Ronnie Mamoepa was quoted by South
African Press Association as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Currently the U.N. has deployed a force in Angola and there has been no
request for further deployment of troops in Angola."
</P>
<P>
Mamoepa said South Africa unequivocally threw its weight behind
statements made by the president of the U.N. Security Council calling
for the observation and implementation of the Lusaka Protocol, the
demobilization of warring parties and an end to hostilities.
</P>
<P>
"We remain convinced that the ultimate solution remains a peaceful
negotiated settlement," Mamoepa said.
</P>
<P>
Angola was plunged back into civil war between the government and the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) in the past
nine months.
</P>
<P>
Many of the rebel UNITA troops failed to demobilize and disarm in
line with the Lusaka Protocol signed in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
