<HEADLINE> U.N. Sanctions Committee Accused of Blocking Iraqi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Saturday accused the
U.N. Sanctions Committee of obstructing contracts it signed with
world companies under the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed Iraqi Trade Ministry official told the Iraqi News
Agency that the U.S. representative in the Sanctions Committee
deliberately held back the punctual delivery of food, medicine
and humanitarian supplies to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Until the end of 1998, the Sanctions Committee had blocked 193
contracts which Iraq signed with foreign companies under the
second, third and fourth phases of oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Of the 193 contracts, 60 were for purchasing food and medicine
and 133 for oil spare parts badly needed for increasing its
production capacity.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food program, which had been in force since
December 1996, allows Iraq to export a limited amount of oil in
every six months to buy food, medicine and other daily necessities
for its 22 million people. Under the program, the U.N. had allowed
Iraq to export 2.2 billion U.S. dollars in each of the first two
six-months and from the third phase, starting early in 1998,
onward, the amount increased to 5.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The current fifth phase of the program came into force on
November 25 of last year.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi official said the U.S. hostile attitude toward Iraq
"is another evidence of the U.S. aggressive policy to kill the
innocent Iraqis."
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. resorted to different means to enforce its
aggressive policy by prolonging sanctions, putting contracts on
hold and launching military attacks on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and British forces raided Iraq for four consecutive
nights on December 16-19 in an operation code-named "Desert Fox."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
