<DOCNO> XIE19990103.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Capital Depends on Wells to Ease Water Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here, Nkhangaa said the
country plans to drill 250 new wells, finish 23 wells under
construction and rehabilitate 200 existing wells as a measure of
dismissing worries of three million Dar es Salaam residents.
</P>
<P>
When all these wells are completed, a total of 22.5 million gallons
of water will be produced per day, compared with 18 million gallons
at present, he said.
</P>
<P>
The water projects need a cost of 3.8 billion Shillings (about 5.58
million U.S. Dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on residents in the city to save water by using treated water
for irrigation and car washing, and appealed to people to understand the
current problem and avoid being selfish in using water at will.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the situation at Ruvu river, the source of water for Dar es
Salaam and Coast regions, the minister said the water level has
dropped to 15.8 meters above level, against a normal level of above 16
meters.
</P>
<P>
Nkhangaa attributed the fall of water level to the below-average
precipitation during the short rains season starting November last
year. "We are now praying for long rains starting in January to March,
otherwise the possibility of drought is 100 percent," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government has sent a team of experts to the
Ruvu River to see if there is an alternative to make the river produce
more water.
</P>
<P>
The experts are expected to make recommendations in two to three
days, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the permanent solution to water shortage in Dar es Salaam
is to build more water works in the upper reaches of Ruvu. However, he
said poverty is the major problem in Tanzania. "If money will be
obtained, the problem will be solved quickly."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said the government has decided to privatize the Dar
es Salaam Water and Sewerage Authority (DAWASA) by the end of this year or
early next year to increase production of water, expand the service and
renovate water plants.
</P>
<P>
DAWASA has said it will supply water on rationing basis whenever
necessary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
