<HEADLINE> S. African Police Probe Cape Town Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 2 (Xinhua) -- South African police are
examining photographs and video footage of Friday's bomb blast in Cape Town,
in the hope of identifying those responsible, local media
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association quoted police spokeswoman Anine de Beer
as saying that bomb experts were still trying to establish what
sort of explosive device was used and forensic experts from Pretoria
would assist in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
She said the bomb was believed to have been placed in the boot of a
stolen Toyota which was parked in Cape Town's most popular tourist
attraction known as the Victoria and Alfred Waterfront.
</P>
<P>
Two people were slightly injured and three cars were badly damaged. So
far nobody has claimed responsibility for the explosion.
</P>
<P>
Friday's blast was the second in the area in five months. A pipe
bomb placed in an American-franchised Planet Hollywood restaurant
claimed two lives and left 26 injured in August.
</P>
<P>
After the August incident, security in the area was beefed up with
surveillance cameras being installed, patrols stepped up and sniffer
dogs deployed.
</P>
<P>
Police believe that the examination of video tapes could provide
some clues for the latest blast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
