<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Socialist Party to Leave the Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' Socialist Edek Party is
considering leaving the government, said party leader Vasos
Lyssarides Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, tabled to the Central Committee of the party, has
gained overwhelming support from party members, Lyssarides told
reporters after a party convention which started Saturday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
It came after President Glafcos Clerides announced his decision
not to deploy Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles, ordered
by the Cyprus government in January 1997 in a bid to cement its
air defense capability.
</P>
<P>
Turkey had threatened to launch preemptive strikes, should the
missiles arrive on the island. Other countries, including the
U.S. and Britain, have voiced objections to the purchase of the
missiles, saying it would increase tensions in the region.
</P>
<P>
The party joins in the government by holding two ministerial
portfolios when President Clerides was re-elected in February 1998
for a second five-year term.
</P>
<P>
Lyssarides said the decision not to deploy the missiles
in Cyprus was wrong and warned of dire consequences for Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He said that the decision, declared in late December 1998,
will inevitably be interpreted as "an adjustment to pressure and
threats from Turkey and others". 
</P>
