<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti-Jordanian Ties to Be Resumed: Kuwaiti FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's First Deputy Prime
Minister and Foreign Minister Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah
said here Sunday that relations between Kuwait and Jordan would be
resumed if his Jordanian counterpart pays a visit to Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question, after a parliament meeting, on
resuming the bilateral ties and reopen the Jordanian embassy
here, Sabah said "when the Jordanian foreign minister comes to
Kuwait everything will end."
</P>
<P>
He has invited Abdul Ilah al-Khatib to come to visit Kuwait,
the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti foreign minister also praised the recent
statements made by Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan on the issue of
Kuwaiti and other detainees in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the Arab Parliament Union meeting convened in
Amman last Monday to examine the situation in Iraq after the
U.S.-British military strikes, Hassan said that "all the Kuwaiti
and Arab detainees must return to their homelands."
</P>
<P>
Bilateral relations between Kuwait and Jordan were severed
after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990 when Amman, along with few
other Arab states, sided with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A reconciliation process between the two countries began in
May 1997 when Kuwait declared it "likes to improve ties with all
Arab countries except Saddam's Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Since then the two sides have exchanged a number of
middle-level visits. 
