<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Exports to Grow 3 Percent This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exports are expected
to grow by 3 percent because of improving domestic factors, the
Department of Business Economics said.
</P>
<P>
The revival of local financial institutions, a stable baht and
improved efficiency by exporters are behind the optimistic
forecast, said Karun Kittisataporn, the department's
director-general, as quoted by Thai News Agency Sunday.
</P>
<P>
As government measures to reform the domestic financial sector
bear fruit, local lenders are expected to resume extending credit
to exporters. As well, the stability of the baht would improve
Thai exporters' confidence in entering new transactions with
foreigners, Karun said.
</P>
<P>
Many exporters postponed transactions in 1998 because of
fluctuations in the value of the baht, especially in the first
half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Changes of one or two baht to the U.S. dollar in a single day
made it very difficult for exporters to calculate costs and
prices.
</P>
<P>
"A group of exporters who attend a seminar held in December by
the department on export prospects in 1999 felt the baht had
already stabilized," Karun said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the exporters complained that the current
rate of the baht, at around 36 to the dollar, was too strong. They
favored a rate closer to 39.
</P>
<P>
Thai exporters had developed greater flexibility, particularly
in marketing, as a result of managing their businesses amid the
domestic economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Despite stiff competition in the world market, many had
maintained impressive market shares in major destinations such as
the United States, the European Union and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The estimated 54-billion-dollar value of exports in 1998 was
six percent lower than in the previous year, but the department
was sticking with its forecast of three percent growth for this
year.
</P>
<P>
This was not quite as optimistic as the 5.2 percent growth rate
foreseen by the National Economic and Social Development Board.
</P>
<P>
In the first 10 months of 1998, exports in baht terms were up
by 3.6 percent on the same period in 1997 to 1.91 trillion baht
(53 billion U.S. dollars). But in dollar terms there was a 6.4
percent decline to 45.27 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exports in October alone were down by 12.7 percent from the
same period of 1997 to 4.83 billion dollars. The agricultural and
agro-industry sector showed a big drop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
