<DOCNO> XIE19990103.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MOFTEC Official Addresses Cross-Straits Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese mainland and Taiwan
Province have enjoyed a boom in trade and business exchanges over
the past two decades, according An Ming, an official with the
Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
An Ming, a MOFTEC assistant minister, said that cross-Straits
trade hit 19.84 billion US dollars in 1997, up dramatically on
only 77 million dollars in 1978.
</P>
<P>
The accumulated trade volume during the 20 years ending
November of 1998 reached 134.71 billion US dollars, including
mainland exports totalling 21.6 billion dollars to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Cross-straits trade enabled the island province to achieve a
surplus, said An. He added that funds and management expertise
from Taiwan have contributed to the mainland's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
He said historical changes have taken place in cross-Straits
relations since January 1, 1979, when the National People's
Congress Standing Committee issued its "Message to Compatriots in
Taiwan". The message called for a halt to decades of hostilities
and the establishment of direct mail service, trade, air and
shipping services.
</P>
<P>
Cross-straits trade and business exchanges have contributed to
the common development of the two sides and have laid a solid
material foundation for the peaceful reunification of the
motherland, said An.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 20 years, The mainland has adopted a series of
laws and and regulations to encourage investments from Taiwan and
protect the rights and interests of investors.
</P>
<P>
Mainland authorities had approved a total of 41,115 projects
involving investment from the island province by the end of
November 1998. An said the mainland has actually used 21.1 billion
US dollars in investments from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that political disputes between the two sides
should neither affect nor interfere with cross-Straits economic
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990103.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Iraq vs. U.S. in Rocky 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 3 (Xinhua) -- 1998 featured intensive
diplomatic maneuvering and military standoff between Iraq and the
U.S., which eventually led to the U.S.-British air raids against
Iraq in the waning days of the year.
</P>
<P>
Three crises over U.N. weapons inspections, crowned by two
military confrontations and an air strike, are surely what the
past year is to be remembered.
</P>
<P>
All these came as a desperate Iraq, already crippled by the
eight-year-old U.N. sanctions, was striving to have the embargo
lifted, while the U.S. appeared preferring to keep the lid on
President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad said it had fully complied with the U.N. resolutions
which ended the Gulf War sparked by Iraq's 1990 invasion of
Kuwait, and eliminated all its weapons of mass destruction, thus
demanding the sanctions be removed.
</P>
<P>
It accused the U.S. of obstructing, both in the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) overseeing the disarmament process and in the
U.N. Security Council, a fair evaluation of Iraq's disarmament
progress in the past eight years, and of trying to prolong the
sufferings of Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions can only be called off by the Security Council
after UNSCOM certifies that Iraq has scrapped all its long-range
missiles, and nuclear, chemical and biological arsenals.
</P>
<P>
In the beginning of last year, Iraq denied U.N. weapons
inspectors access to presidential sites, setting off a military
standoff with the U.S., which had stepped up military buildup in
the Gulf. Saddam backed down after U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan brokered a deal hinting there could be a comprehensive
review in the near future.
</P>
<P>
But in August, talks between Iraq and UNSCOM over disarmament
achievements broke down and Baghdad announced to suspend
cooperation with U.N. weapons inspectors. It called for a
restructuring of UNSCOM, which it alleged served U.S. interests
rather than the U.N..
</P>
<P>
On October 31, Baghdad, with its hope for a comprehensive
review dashed, further decided to halt activities of U.N. weapons
inspectors in Iraq. The U.S. again got ready to deliver its threat
of a punitive military attack.
</P>
<P>
Iraq reversed its decision at the last minute just to avert an
imminent air bombardment by the U.S. and Britain on November
14. Exasperated by Saddam's playing of "mouse and cat," the
U.S. threatened that any future strikes would be "without
pre-warning."
</P>
<P>
The time finally came a month later. On December 16, no sooner
had UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler reported to the Security
Council that Baghdad renegaded its promises and did not fully
cooperate in weapons inspections, than U.S. President Bill Clinton
called the shoot.
</P>
<P>
The four-night-long Operation Desert Fox dealt another blow to
a weakened Iraq, but also fueled questioning over U.S. motives and
justification for the use of force, and set rift in the Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
Some believed the air strike lacked U.N. authorization and was
executed without provocation, and others asserted that its timing
was dubious because Clinton was facing impeachment in the House of
Representatives for "perjury" and "obstruction of justice."
</P>
<P>
What made U.S. objectives hazier and more elusive was that
Clinton publicly announced that his administration would plot for
the overthrow of Saddam, in collaboration with Iraqi opposition
factions, a tactic used but failed.
</P>
<P>
As Washington claimed victory and said the strike further
weakened Saddam and put back his lethal weapons ability, most
people are almost certain that it did little in solving any
problems, but killed the weapons monitoring regime that had been
hailed as "effective" in the past eight years and made a defiant
Saddam even more defiant.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. cruise missiles, Iraq claimed, hit places under
permanent U.N. monitoring, which made no sense, and U.N. weapons
inspectors, order to evacuate for the second time in a year by
Butler before the attack began, are now unable to return.
</P>
<P>
Iraq challenged the U.S. by declaring it does not recognize the
"no-fly" zones, imposed by the U.S. and its allies in the south
and north of its territory soon after the Gulf War, saying they
were without U.N. mandate and therefore "illegal," and began
firing at patrolling allied warplanes last week.
</P>
<P>
And the air strike goes well beyond the Iraqi issue by setting
a dangerous precedent for some powers to get around the Security
Council and take unilateral actions against an independent
sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
The other permanent members of the Security Council - Russia,
France and China - had repeatedly called for a peaceful solution
to the confrontations, a fair comprehensive review of what Iraq
has achieved in ridding weapons of mass destruction and a
relaxation and early lifting of the harsh sanctions.
</P>
<P>
They demanded that Iraq comply fully with the U.N. resolutions
in order to close each and every prohibited weapon file so that
Iraqi people's ordeal can be put to an end and the country can
return as a member of the international community.
</P>
<P>
But if the U.S. and Britain go their own way of "containment"
against Iraq and continue flexing their muscles, and if Iraq keeps
pushing brinkmanship, the year 1999 threatens to be rockier than
1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990103.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guizhou Achieves Grain Self-sufficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guizhou
Province has achieved grain self-sufficiency as a result of good
harvests over the past six years.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou's 1998 grain output hit 11 million tons, or more than
350 kg per capita in rural areas, according to provincial Party
secretary Liu Fangren.
</P>
<P>
"Guizhou's grain imports from other parts of China are
essentially limited to levels needed to regulate varieties,"
according to Liu.
</P>
<P>
The province's grain production stood at 10 million tons
annually between 1995-1997.
</P>
<P>
Liu also said the 1998 per capita net income of farmers grew
four percent on the previous year's level of 1,298 yuan. In
addition, the number of rural residents living in absolute poverty
dropped from 50 percent in the early 1990s to around 10 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou, one of China's most underdeveloped provinces, covers
176,000 sq. kilometers. Karst formations cover some 73 percent of
the province's total land area, with poor geological conditions
formerly requiring the province to import grain.
</P>
<P>
Liu attributed Guizhou's increased grain production in recent
years to rising investments in agriculture and accelerated efforts
to improve land conditions. Related efforts have in turn resulted
in the substantial increase in per unit output.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
