<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Purchase of Ballistic Missile from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Sunday denied a Japanese
television report that Tehran had purchased ballistic missiles
from the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi termed the
report as "unfounded," and said the Islamic Republic of Iran has
announced time and again that it has no missile cooperation with
other countries, including the DPRK, the Islamic Republic News
Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The Japan broadcasting corporation (NHK) reported on Saturday
that the DPRK has built 30 of its first-generation ballistic
Rodong missiles and exported some of them to Iran and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, spokesman of the Iranian Defense Ministry Kivan
Khosrow said that Iran has never purchased any missile from the
DPRK and the report by foreign media in this regard was a "mere
lie."
</P>
<P>
Iran does not need to buy missiles from any country and it has
the capability to meet the defensive needs, he said, adding that
a country, which can produce a long-range missile like the
Shahab-3 (Meteor-3), does not need to buy missiles from other
countries.
</P>
<P>
Last July, Iran tested its first missile of Shahab-3 with a
range of 1,300 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Tehran said that the missile was designed and produced by
Iranian experts, but western reports said that the missile was
produced with assistance from other countries.
</P>
<P>
Khosrow said that at the time of the test, "some foreign media
affiliating to the Zionist (Israeli) circles also claimed that
the test was not successful."
</P>
<P>
At the meantime, they also claimed that the missile was a
threat to the region, the spokesman said, adding that such
anti-Iran propaganda is doomed to failure because the regional
countries have shown their positive reaction to Iran's defensive
capabilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
