<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haikou Enjoys Healthy Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Haikou, capital of south China's
Hainan Province, continues to enjoy an unprecedented economic
growth momentum due to years of restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary figures show that the city's gross domestic product
grew by a healthy 8.6 percent in 1998, compared to the national
level 7.8 percent. The 1997 growth stood at 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The relatively high economic growth rates over the past two
years resulted from extensive economic restructuring carried out
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
The city's economy registered a record annual increase of 83.3
percent in the early 1990s due to the unchecked real estate
bubble, according to one local official.
</P>
<P>
Haikou's economic growth plunged to 3.9 percent in 1993 and 3.5
percent in 1994 as a result of a prevailing credit squeeze, with
the figure falling to only one percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Starting in 1996, Haikou has introduced a number of measures to
reform the state-owned sector, including mergers, bankruptcies,
asset restructuring and auctions. Consequently, the average
liability-asset ratio of state-owned enterprises has dropped from
89 percent to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Haikou's state-owned enterprises succeeded in reversing losses
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The city has attached great importance to introducing high
technology, and to controlling pollution, according to the
official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
