<HEADLINE> Guiyang Uses Overseas Funds for Infrastructure Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Guizhou, capital city of
southwest China's Guizhou Province, has effectively used overseas
funds for infrastructure improvement projects.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Development Bank and Japan have pledged to provide
close to a third of the 4.8 billion yuan used to construct the
expressway linking Guiyang with Xinzai, a city on the border with
the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, according to Guiyang Mayor
Sun Guoqiang.
</P>
<P>
Sun said construction of the 260-km expressway will be
completed in three years.
</P>
<P>
Construction of a major water treatment plant in the western
suburbs will be completed at an estimated cost of 1.07 billion
yuan, including Japanese loans totalling 5.5 billion yen, said Sun.
</P>
<P>
"China's strategy of attracting increased investment to promote
economic growth has created unprecedented opportunities for
Guiyang," according to Sun.
</P>
<P>
He said Guiyang plans to introduce more policies to encourage
the influx in overseas capital for infrastructure sectors such as
transportation, telecommunications and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
China and Japan have agreed on launching a number of
environmental protection projects in the city. Total investments
of two billion yuan, including Japanese government loans totalling
100 million US dollars, according to Sun.
</P>
<P>
He added that arrangements for BOT (build-operate-transfer)
projects and various other forms of cooperation include the
increased use of overseas capital.  
</P>
</TEXT>
