<DOCNO> XIE19990103.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Announces New Code on Take-overs, Mergers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The new Malaysian Code on
Take-overs and Mergers 1998 became effective January 1, 1999,
Malaysia's Securities Commission (SC) announced.
</P>
<P>
The new code, replacing the Malaysian Code on Take-overs and
Mergers 1987, seeks to ensure that minority shareholders are given
a fair opportunity to consider the merits and demerits of an offer
and to enable them to decide whether they should retain or dispose
of their shares, the SC said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The new code has new provisions relating to "creeping"
take-overs which have been amended to allow an acquirer who holds
between 33 percent and 50 percent of the voting shares in a
company to acquire two percent within a period of six months
instead of 12 months. Such persons were not allowed to acquire
more than two percent of the voting shares in the company in any
12-month period previously.
</P>
<P>
This would effectively reduce the time taken to "creep" into
control of the company.
</P>
<P>
The SC said the amendment was made in order to be more
consistent with international practices such as those of Hong
Kong, Singapore and Australia.
</P>
<P>
The new code is a testimony of the commitment of the SC towards
ensuring higher standards of disclosure and corporate behavior and
greater professionalism from all involved in mergers and
acquisitions, SC Chairman Mohd Munir Majid said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the SC also announced that approving a proposal
submitted by the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange to amend its Listing
Requirements. The Listing Requirements, part of the regulatory
framework governing take-overs and mergers, are amended
consequently to the coming into force of the new code. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
