<HEADLINE> Netanyahu's Former Aide Launches New Immigrant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 3 (Xinhua) -- One of Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu's former aides launched a new immigrant party
Sunday to compete in the upcoming elections, posing a threat to
the largest existing immigrant party.
</P>
<P>
Avigdor Lieberman, Netanyahu's former director-general,
announced at a news conference the establishment of Yisrael
Beiteinu, or Israel Is Our Home, a right-wing immigrants' party
with a platform focusing on social justice.
</P>
<P>
His party is expected to split the votes of Yisrael Baaliya, a
party representing immigrants from former Soviet Union and headed
by Trade and Industry Minister Natan Sharansky.
</P>
<P>
Sharansky, whose party occupies seven seats in the parliament,
has failed in his efforts to put pressure on Netanyahu to
dissuade Lieberman from establishing a new party.
</P>
<P>
Lieberman's office said that while there is "coordination"
between him and his former boss, Netanyahu, the party is
completely independent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local daily The Jerusalem Post reported Sunday that
Leah Rabin, the widow of former prime minister Yitzhak Rabin, has
said that former chief of general staff Amnon Lipkin-Shahak must
join Labor Party leader Ehud Barak in the elections.
</P>
<P>
Her position would put more pressure on the popular former
military chief to join Labor and not to split the center and
left. Shahak and Barak were both preteges of Rabin.
</P>
<P>
Shahak has rejected the invitation from Barak to join the
Labor and is expected to announce his candidacy for prime
minister at the head of a new centrist party Tuesday or
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He and Likud defector Dan Meridor, who is also forming a
centrist party, have held rounds of talks to coordinate their
campaign but failed to reach agreement on issues like when to
unite their forces and who should be the head of the list.
</P>
