<HEADLINE> Iran Calls on Pakistan to Mend Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi Sunday called on the Pakistani government to take
"practical steps" to mend the strained relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Only "practical steps" by Islamabad can repair the ties between
the two neighbors, Kharrazi told visiting Pakistani Foreign
Secretary Shamshad Ahmad Khan.
</P>
<P>
Despite the close bonds between the two nations, he said,
terrorist activities in Pakistan had left adverse impacts on
Pakistan's national interests, security and its relations with
Iran, the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi urged Islamabad to take practical and urgent action to
punish those responsible for the killing of Iranian nationals in
Pakistan to appease the public opinion in Iran.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past years, terrorist operations in Pakistan have
hurt the feelings of the Iranian nation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and Pakistan soured following a series
of killings of Iranians living in Pakistan and the slayings of
Iranian diplomats and a reporter in Afghanistan by the
Pakistani-backed Taliban militia last August.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years, a number of Iranian nationals were
killed in Pakistan. In the latest incident in February last year,
two Iranian engineers in charge of a bridge construction in
Karachi were shot dead by unidentified gunmen.
</P>
<P>
Iran has lodged strong protest to Islamabad and urged it to
take serious measures to punish the killers and ensure security
for Iranians in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ahmad Khan said Islamabad-Tehran ties were based on
numerous historical, cultural and religious commonalities and
voiced his government's resolve to remove the existing
misunderstandings and indignation hidering bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government is determined to investigate the
killing incidents and punish the terrorists, he said, expressing
regret that some deficiencies in the Pakistani judicial system had
caused failures or delays in prosecuting the terrorists.
</P>
<P>
Ahman Khan arrived here Saturday morning to convey a message
from Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif to Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami. 
</P>
</TEXT>
