<HEADLINE> Oman to Curb Software Piracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Oman will take actions to curb
software piracy as an effort toward joining the World Trade
Organization (WTO), the Gulf News of the United Arab Emirate
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We are now set to cleanse the software market," Mudrik Al
Musawi, the director of Agencies and Trademarks of Commerce and
Industry Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
"The elimination of software piracy is a must to join the
WTO," he said.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the importance to implement the Copyright Law enacted
in Oman last June, Musawi said the law was a prerequisite for a
country to join the WTO.
</P>
<P>
He added that he is not in a position to give a specific date
for the ban. "All I can say is that it will be done as soon as
possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
Al Musawi said Oman has imposed a new year ban on pirated
video-tapes and audio-cassettes.
</P>
<P>
Inspection teams started raiding shops in Muscat on
Saturday. "We shall not sit idle until each and every shop sells
genuine cassettes," Al Musawi said. 
</P>
