<HEADLINE> 10,000 Workers to Be Retrenched in Singapore in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's top union leader
has expected more workers will be retrenched in Singapore in 1999
and predicted the retrenchment figure will be over 10,000.
</P>
<P>
Lim Boon Heng, secretary-general of the National Trades Union
Congress (NTUC) and minister without portfolio, said at a local
ceremony Sunday that his prediction was based on retrenchment
figures before the economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
In 1998 alone, an estimated 25,000 workers lost their jobs in
the city state.
</P>
<P>
But Lim said the current economic downturn has not been as
difficult on workers as expected according to initial feedback
received by NTUC from its members.
</P>
<P>
Citing the expected very low or no growth in the country's
economy, Lim urged moderation in wage expectation.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Ministry of Trade and Industry has forecast that
Singapore economy will grow by between minus one percent to plus
one percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Lim also promised to help workers and their families in
difficulties, saying that NTUC plans to raise a few million
Singapore dollars to provide children of unions members with
education grants.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted the number of education applicants is not as
high as projected, suggesting things are not as difficult as
feared. 
</P>
</TEXT>
