<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agricultural Inputs Still Dog Zambian Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LUSAKA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Thirty four years after independence,
Zambia's agricultural sector is still characterized by desperate cries
from farmers over the no-availability or late delivery of inputs, Sunday
Times of Zambia reported.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted agricultural sector insiders as attributing this
perennial problem to a number of factors which need lasting solutions,
otherwise there may be an adverse effect on the country's food security.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Cooperative Federation managing director , Grieve Sibale said
the
inputs problem is likely to remain unchanged as long as the there is no
body set up to deal specifically with it.
</P>
<P>
"Each year we have this problem of inputs, it is either they come late
or when they do come, then we have distribution bottlenecks. This problem
is likely to be there as long as there is no institution to deal with
inputs specifically," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sibale said that the problem has been further exacerbated by the
increasingly prevalent loans defaulting culture among some farmers
especially small scale ones, who are unwilling to repay their loans even if
they have a bumper harvest.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the need for a streamlined approach to the inputs issue,
Zambia National Farmers Union (ZNFU) chief, Ajay Vashee, said that at the
moment, a clear-cut policy relating to this is lacking.
</P>
<P>
He noted that although the market might have been liberalized and there
are now a number of private sector players, there appears to be no guiding
parameters within which they can operate.
</P>
<P>
Vashee proposed establishing a national fertilizer committee to be
composed of representatives from the government and fertilizer dealers, the
ZNFU and other interested parties.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, while acknowledging the necessity of private sector
participation in the agricultural sector, veteran leader of Truckers
Association of Zambia, Charles Madondo, said that this involvement has on
the
whole, had a very token effect.
</P>
<P>
Madondo, who has had a 30 year involvement in the agriculture marketing
sector, noted that the private participants concentrate their efforts
in urban and peri-urban areas at the expense of the productive rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Expressing similar views, Program Against Malnutrition director Friday
Luhila said the private sector appears to be more interested in selling and
battering agricultural products instead of ensuring inputs reaching their
intended beneficiaries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
