<HEADLINE> Bombings of Iraq Not to Ease Tensions: UAE Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Sporadic bombings of Baghdad
will do nothing for easing tensions between the U.S., Britain and
Iraq, United Arab Emirate's Ambassador to Britain Easa Saleh Al
Gurg was quoted Sunday as saying.
</P>
<P>
While acknowledging the special relationship between the UAE
and Britain, Al Gurg said the current tactics being adopted by
Washington and London had proved harmful to the Iraqi people and
not to bring the conflict closer to a resolution, Dubai-based Gulf
News reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The situation has to be looked at on a deeper level. If the
present approach was achieving something, then it would be fine.
But killing 50 people here and 100 people there is not the way,"
said Al Gurg.
</P>
<P>
Al Gurg said that UAE nationals sympathized with Iraqis
affected by sanctions and intermittent air strikes, but also
enjoyed fruitful and historical trade and cultural ties with
Britain.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain launched air strikes on Iraq for four
consecutive nights on December 16-19, with a declared aim of
punishing it for not cooperating with U.N. weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
The inspections began in 1991 after the Gulf War, sparked by
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990, to ensure Iraq's elimination of
all weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
