<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Says No to Meeting Sharon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright has refused to meet with Israeli Foreign
Minister Ariel Sharon during his upcoming visit to the United
States, English-language paper the Jerusalem Post reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Sharon is scheduled to travel to New York this week to attend
a convention of Israeli consuls-general, and efforts were made to
arrange a meeting with Albright during his stay.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted U.S. sources as saying that Sharon wanted to
discuss final status topics with his U.S. counterpart, but his
request was rejected. He was told that there was no reason to
talk about final status matters while Israel refused to implement
even the interim agreements.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Washington viewed with gravity the freeze in
the peace process that was announced on the heels of
U.S. President Bill Clinton's visit to the region last month, as
well as reports of increased building activities in Jewish
settlements.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration has not openly accused Israel of
sabotaging the process in order to avoid the appearance of
interventing in Israeli electoral politics. But the U.S. does
view Israel as responsible for the collapse of the Wye accords.
</P>
<P>
U.S. sources stressed that the Wye accords, achieved with
maximal U.S. involvement, was approved by the Israeli government
and Knesset (parliament), and there was no reason to freeze its
implementation.
</P>
<P>
Under the Wye accord signed with the Palestinians in October,
Israel should withdraw from another 13 percent of the West Bank in
three stages.
</P>
<P>
After carrying out the first phase of the withdrawal, Israel
suspended the implementation of the second phase, citing
Palestinians' failure to stop anti-Israel rhetoric and cancel the
plan to declare an independent state next May.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Palestinians are preparing for a joint
Clinton-Arafat summit sometime in March or April, which will
discuss issues including the halt in the peace process and its
ramifications for the expiration of the Oslo accords on May 4.
</P>
<P>
Saeb Arekat, head of the Palestinian negotiation team, termed
on Saturday the expansion of settlements, expropriation of lands
and demolition of Palestinan houses a "declaration of war against
the Palestinian people."
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Friday after its weekly meeting, the
cabinet of the Palestinian National Authority said "the
government of Israel will bear responsibility for the implications
of freezing the Wye Memorandum and the vicious settlement
offensive waged against the Palestinian lands."
</P>
<P>
Media reports said that during 1998, about 9,000 housing units
were build for Jewish settlers in the territories, and tenders
for construction at Har Homa will be completed this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
