<HEADLINE> China's Army-to-Army Foreign Relations Forge Ahead (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- China's military relations with
other countries left the world impressed last year with active
and fruitful exchanges and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here say that the Chinese People's Liberation Army's
(PLA) active relations with foreign armies have enhanced mutual
understanding and trust, and at the same time demonstrated China's
sincerity in seeking a long-term peaceful environment in both
neighboring regions of Asia and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
During the past year, the PLA welcomed 75 ranking army groups
from over 50 countries, and sent more than 30 delegations led by
senior PLA officers to visit over 60 countries. Moreover, the PLA
carried out some 180 exchanges of visits with the armies of over
50 countries in special professional fields including technology,
culture and art.
</P>
<P>
Particularly, analysts called attention to the PLA's fruitful
exchanges and cooperation with some major countries, noting that
they have done well in promoting the establishment and development
of China's partnership with these powers.
</P>
<P>
Sino-U.S. army relations witnessed a comprehensive growth
following the resumption of such relations in 1997. U.S. Defense
Secretary William Cohen visited China in early 1998, whereas
General Zhang Wannian, vice-chairman of the Chinese Central
Military Commission, made a trip to the United States in
September, which produced arrangements, in line with the consensus
the two presidents reached concerning military relations, to add
new substantial contents to the further growth of army-to-army
exchanges and cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
