<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banks Plan Remedies for Bad Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- China is planning organizations
similar to bridging banks, to rescue staggering amounts of bad
loans that are sapping the strength of State-owned commercial
banks, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The China Construction Bank (CCB), one of the country's biggest
State-owned commercial banks, is creating a separate organ within
itself to resuscitate its non-performing assets.
</P>
<P>
The proposal for such institutions is being supported by the
central government. Other commercial banks will likely set up
similar institutions of their own.
</P>
<P>
The new internal bank is expected to go to work soon, but it's
uncertain if it will be a bridging bank or an assets management
company specializing in the treatment of bad loans, a CCB
official said.
</P>
<P>
Wang Songqi, deputy director of the Financial Research Center
of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, is quoted as saying
that the success of the new organization is believed to hinge on
the actual internal mechanism and the necessary protection of law.
</P>
<P>
Against banking rules, vested interest groups and lobbying
concerning personal benefits have interfered in lending and
debt-clearing affairs for years, the newspaper noted.
</P>
<P>
And it is hard to be 100 percent impartial in selecting
professional managers for the new organization, if the CCB is to
follow the examples of the United States and Sweden, where bad
loans are bought at a discount, regrouped or managed by
specialized companies made up of experts, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
A big leap in the action is that the government has at last
started the painful process of slicing off the ailing parts of
State-owned bank's lending, Wang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
