<DOCNO> XIE19990103.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Tanzania's Economic Growth Slows Down in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 3 (Xinhua) --The growth rate of
Tanzania's economy, which remains heavily dependent on
agriculture, has slowed down over the past year due to the El
Nino related bad weather.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania failed to achieve a porjected five percent economic
growth rate due to devastating floods between late l997 and early
this year which paralyzed roads, railways and bridges and
affected movement of goods for both imports and exports.
</P>
<P>
The 1997/98 fiscal year ending June 30 with an economic growth
rate of 3.5 percent was seen as a recessional year in Tanzania,
compared to the previous two years with economic growth rates of
4.2 and 4.0 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian Central Bank said in its latest monthly economic
review that export receipts declined by 18.7 percent during 1997/98
to 644.9 million U.S.Dollars from 793.7 million recorded in the
previous year, with both traditional and non-traditional exports
performing poorly.
</P>
<P>
Government revenue reached about 930 million Dollars, below
the target of one billion Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture contributes around 55 percent of the country's
gross domestic product (GDP), employs 80 percent of the labor
force and accounts for 58 percent of its export earnings.
</P>
<P>
Affected by floods, growth of agriculture which lacks modern
irrigation systems, slowed down to 2.5 percent in 1998 from 3.6
percent in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
In his new year message delivered on January 2, Tanzanian
President Benjamin Mkapa said that his country is short of up to
450,000 tons of food due to adverse weather and destructive
pests.
</P>
<P>
Continuing floods had caused up to 30 percent or more losses
to some agricultural crops. Hardest hit were cotton and coffee,
Tanzania's key foreign exchange earners.
</P>
<P>
The output of cotton lint, called "white gold" by Tanzanians,
dropped to 69,970 tons in 1997/98 from 84,500 tons in the 1996/97
season, the Tanzanian Cotton and Seed Board disclosed.
</P>
<P>
As the country's leading cash crop, coffee accounts for nearly
20 percent of the country's foreign exchange earnings estimated
at about 700 million Dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Due to the bad weather, coffee's output went down to 38,000 tons
in 1997/98 from 41,000 tons in the previous season.
</P>
<P>
Export earnings from coffee, cotton and cashew nuts declined
by 5.7 percent, 33.8 percent and 27 percent respectively when
compared with levels recorded during the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Observers said that had it not been for El Nino, Tanzania's
economy could have moved onto the fast track. Tanzania's future
looks fine as bright aspects lie in its potential.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990103.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Tanzania's Economic Growth Slows Down in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The potential exists in, among others, encouraging political
situation, macro-economic stability and bold economic reform
steps.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has enjoyed high-level stability as opposed to
neighboring Burundi, Rwanda and the Democratic Republic of Congo.
Even other two east African neighbors, Kenya and Uganda, can't be
a match for Tanzania in this regard in the eyes of foreign
diplomats here.
</P>
<P>
Inflation hit a 17-year low to 12.1 percent in last November,
thanks to the tight monetary policies adopted by the government.
</P>
<P>
Bold liberalization steps like the divestiture of the National
Bank of Commerce in October 1997, the establishment of the
Tanzania Investment Center in August 1997, the launching of the
Dar es Salaam Stock Exchange and the adopting of new Mining Act
in April 1998, had satisfied the international financiers and
increased investors' confidence.
</P>
<P>
With more red tapes cut, over 1,000 development projects worth
3.2 billion Dollars have been approved with 168,570 new jobs to
be created, since the former Investment Promotion Center was
transformed in August 1997 into Tanzania Investment Center, which
is rather an investment facilitator than a regulator.
</P>
<P>
To ensure economic recovery, President Mkapa has
expressed the determination to continue with the privatization
drive.
</P>
<P>
The government has started the process to restructure and
eventually privatize utilities such as the Dar es Salaam Water
and Station Authority, Tanzania Harbors Authority, Tanzania
Telecommunications Ltd. and Tanzania Electric Supply Company Ltd.
</P>
<P>
But unusual dry weather linked to La Nina in the past three
months has cast a shadow over the hope for a quick recovery
as the country's economy is generally at the mercy of Mother
Nature.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Tanzania is heavily indebted. Its domestic debt
stood at 1.4 billion Dollars in late October, up by 8.7 percent
as compared to that of the corresponding period of the previous
year, while its external debt reached 8.28 billion Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, economic analysts here still fear that if the rain
season next year from March to May continues to be unusually dry,
the economic prospect could become doubtful in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
