<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Revenue Earnings Lag Behind Target in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh collected 53.23 billion
taka (1.10 billion U.S. dollars) as revenue earnings during the
first five month of the current fiscal year, 10 percent short of
the targeted 59.22 billion taka (1.22 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The revenue collection during the July-November period, the
first five months of the 1998-99 fiscal year, however, was 2.57
percent higher than that of the corresponding period of last year,
the English-language The Independent newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Negative growth was recorded at almost all sources of revenue
income, such as import-export tax, customs, value-added tax,
income tax and supplementary duties.
</P>
<P>
The flood hitting the country from July to September in 1998
was a major reason for the shortfall. Fall in export and import
prices in the international market and withdrawal of import duties
from many items after the flood were also responsible for the
shortfall.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's revenue income in the budge for the 1998-99 fiscal
year was projected at 157 billion taka (3.27 billion dollars), 11
percent higher than the actual collection during the previous
financial year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
