<DOCNO> XIE19990103.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Urge Americans to Eat Less Sugar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Leading U.S. experts urged
American people to eat less sugar to avoid obesity and other
health problems, reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
There was medical evidence that diets high in sugar could
promote obesity, kidney stones, osteoporosis, heart disease and
dental problems, leading health and nutrition experts from 46
U.S. health groups said in a letter to the secretaries of the
U.S. Departments of Health and Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
"With all the focus on fat, we've forgotten about sugar. It's
time to rethink our national infatuation with sweets," said
Michael Jacobson, executive director of the Center for Science in
the Public Interest (CSPI).
</P>
<P>
The health experts said soft drinks, with about nine teaspoons
per 12-ounce can, were a main cause of the rise in sugar usage.
Soda could contribute to osteoporosis as many teen-age girls and
women drank sugary soft drinks instead of calcium-rich milk.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.S. Department of Agriculture, a daily diet
of 2,000 calories should include no more than about 10 teaspoons
of added sugar. Surveys conducted by the department show that
most Americans eat roughly double that amount daily. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
