<HEADLINE> India's Trade Deficit May Top 10 Billion US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW DELHI, January 3 (Xinhua) -- India's trade deficit for the
1998-99 fiscal year would climb to an unprecedented level of 10
billion U.S. dollars due to unrelenting increase in non-oil
imports, "The Hindustan Times" said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"If the trend persists and global oil prices climb up, the
country would slide towards a balance of payments (BoP) crisis
which might force recourse to the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) loans as in the case of 1990-91," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The country's trade deficit for the April-November period 1998
has widened to 6.7 billion U.S. dollars as much as the deficit for
whole of 1997-98. According to highly placed government sources,
trade deficit for the 1998-99 fiscal year (April 1 ,1998-March 31,
1999) would exceed 10 billion U.S. dollars as the spurt in non-oil
imports has shown no indication of tapering off.
</P>
<P>
"The frightful trend has triggered off alarm bells at the
ministries of finance and commerce as the country is also under
pressure to scrap all import curbs maintained on BoP grounds," it
s aid.
</P>
<P>
The World Trade Organization's (WTO) ruling in the dispute
with the United States over quantitative restrictions of imports
has also left the government in a sensitive position. Unless an
amicable settlement is worked out with the United States, the
threat of reprisal affecting the country's exports would hang on
precariously.
</P>
<P>
"The picture is not rosy on the exports front as well since
the decline that has been witnessed throughout this financial year
is yet to be stemmed. The decline in exports was highest for the
first quarter at 7.94 percent. Though there has been subsequent
increases and decreases in the level of decline, the constant
factor till now is that negative growth has gripped the sector
firmly," it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
