<HEADLINE> Japan Funds Flood Control Project in S.Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government's
Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund will provide 4072 million
rupees (60 million U.S. dollars) to the Sri Lanka government for
flood control, a ministry communique said.
</P>
<P>
The communique available on Sunday was issued by the Ministry
of Industrial Development. It said the money would be used in the
flood control project in the Dehiwala-Mount Lavinia-Ratmalana and
the Greater Colombo areas.
</P>
<P>
The project will come under the third stage of the Greater
Colombo Flood Control, and in the first stage Dehiwala, Mount
Lavinia, Attidiya and Kawdana areas will be covered, the
communique said.
</P>
<P>
For the past 15 years, these areas have suffered difficulties
due to flooding during rain, the main cause of which due to
unauthorized constructions, closing of the drains by unscrupulous
persons, and neglect of maintenance of canals and drains.
</P>
<P>
In the Kawdana and Attidiya areas several large concrete tanks
will be built to hold the rain water which will then be sent down
through specially prepared pipes to the sea so that these areas
will be flood free in the future, said the communique.
</P>
<P>
Major work on this project will be completed this year. Six
large bridges, several culverts and roads will also be built and
main roads repaired, the communique added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
