<HEADLINE> Thailand Intensifying Anti-drug Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is intensifying
anti-drug efforts to stem the inflow of drugs from neighboring
countries, military sources said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
As part of the anti-drug campaign, the Thai army is stepping up
border checks against drug shipments by smuggling rings which have
turned to new trafficking routes in Northern Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The northernmost province of Kanchanaburi has recently become
a hotbed of drug smuggling as drug rings used the area as a
springboard for the illegal trade, said one source, requesting
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The Thai anti-drug forces arrested a growing number of
suspected drug smugglers in the province in the past year, and
seized 250,000 amphetamine tablets in one single haul on December
22. This was an indication that drug smuggling rings have changed
their route to the region, Third Army Commander Sommai Wichaworn
said earlier.
</P>
<P>
The drugs, which slipped through the border checks, are usually
carried through hill tribe villages along the border before being
taken past mountainous and forest terrain to the plains of
Kamphaeng Phet and on to other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
It has been discovered that drug traders from other provinces
and Bangkok have traveled to these villages to buy the drugs
themselves.
</P>
<P>
The Thai authorities have set up the National Narcotics
Operation Center to counter the mounting illegal trade.
</P>
<P>
The Fourth Infantry Regiment has been instructed to boost
surveillance along the border to stem the flow of the drug on this
route, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The military has divided its operations into two different
targets. Military units will be sent into the area where massive
drug trafficking was reported but will leave the job to the police
and the civilian agencies if the situation was not serious.
</P>
<P>
Sommai admitted that Thailand faced difficulties in stemming
the drug trafficking because of the many trafficking routes and
the high financial return offered in the business. But he said the
Thai military is determined to continue the fight against the
illegal trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
