<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Tax Revenue Increases in 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's total tax revenue
increased to 38.8 billion Kyats (129.3 million U.S. dollars) in
1997-98 fiscal year from 3.4 billion Kyats (11.3 million dollars)
in 1988-89, according to a latest issue of the "Golden Myanmar"
magazine.
</P>
<P>
The magazine attributed the rise to the government's reform of
tax and tariff structure since then, with amendments in tax and
tariff law, enactment of new laws, streamlining and simplification
of procedures in collection of taxes, adjustment of tax rates and
strengthening of tax administration.
</P>
<P>
There are 15 kinds of taxes and duties collected by the
government with the Internal Revenue Department (IRD)
administering five kinds of taxes, which account for about 75
percent of the total tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
The five kinds of taxes collected by the IRD are commodities
and services tax and commercial tax, state lottery, stamp duties,
income tax and profit tax.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, customs duties, collected by the Customs Department,
account for over 20 percent of the total tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
Total duties collected in the 1997-98 were 8.579 billion Kyats
(28.5 million dollars), according to another official statistics.
</P>
</TEXT>
