<HEADLINE> Crime Occurrence Declines in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Altogether 13,487 cases of crime
occurred in Myanmar in 1998, dropping by 9.2 percent and 34.6
percent as compared with that in 1997 and 1996 respectively,
official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Total number of crime cases of 10 major categories throughout
the country was 1,391 in 1998, while there were 2,146 in 1997 and
3,070 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Of them, 179 cases took place in Yangon division in 1998, while
196 registered in 1997 and 398 in 1996 in the division.
</P>
<P>
Success was achieved more in other states and divisions as
compared with Yangon division, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that Myanmar has very few such crime
cases as compared with other parts of the world, especially other
Asian and Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The city of Yangon is known as one of the best 40 Asian cities,
standing at the 7th position of the least occurrence rate of
crimes.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar first formed the Police Force Management System
Reformation Committee in January 1994 and later in October 1996
the country set up another Crime Reduction, Education and
Information Committee for effective prevention of crimes and for
bringing down criminal offenses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
