<HEADLINE> Myanmar Foreign Minister on International Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar will continue to pursue
an independent and active foreign policy, maintain friendly and
cordial relations with all countries, particularly with its
neighbors, said new Myanmar Foreign Minister U Win Aung.
</P>
<P>
U Win Aung, who became foreign minister in a latest reshuffle
of the cabinet in November last year replacing U Ohn Gyaw, made
the remarks when hosting a new year reception here Saturday for
the diplomatic corps in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the relations between Myanmar and its
neighbors as well as with countries in the region continued to be
strengthened through frequent exchange of visits.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that friendly and cooperation with the
European Union and its members and the United States could be
regained as in the previous years.
</P>
<P>
He added that Myanmar hopes to play more active role in the
international relations in the coming years by participating more
extensively and intensively in regional and international forums,
while trying its best to consolidate bilateral relations with all
nations.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, since its independence in 1948, has established
diplomatic ties with 73 countries. In addition to being a member
of the United Nations, Myanmar joined major regional organizations
in 1997 such as the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
and the BIMST-EC, a five-nation South Asian economic organization
comprising of Bangladesh, India, Myanmar, Sri Lanka and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
On domestic affairs, U Win Aung stressed that 1998 was a year
of anniversaries for Myanmar -- Golden Jubilee of Independence,
10th anniversary of coming to power by the military and 1st
anniversary of the formation of the State Peace and Development
Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
