<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Boost Cooperation With China in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's Prime Minster Phan Van
Khai said Saturday that Vietnam will boost cooperation with China
in 1999, considering Sino-Vietnamese relations an important factor
for his country's development.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question by Xinhua on the Vietnam-China relations
at a new year press conference here, the prime minister spoke of
the similarities between the two countries and their joint desire
to promote investment and trade relations toward the goal of 2
billion U.S. dollars in two-way trade by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
He also recalled the favorable developments in solving the
issues in land border and delineation of the Tonkin Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Khai also reaffirmed Vietnam's policy to attach importance to
its friendly and cooperative relations with Laos and Cambodia and
its hope to have a peaceful and friendly border line with
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Answering question on situation in Cambodia, the Vietnamese
prime minister said his country will not interfere in internal
affairs of Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam hoped Cambodia will restore earlier its peace and
stability, so as the Cambodian government and people will focus on
its national construction.
</P>
<P>
In reply to a Japanese reporter, Khai said the agreement
Vietnam signed with Russia on the Cam Ranh Bay in central Vietnam
would continue to be implemented to 2004 as agreed previously
without any change made during a visit by the Russian defense
minister in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
