<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Senate Speaker Says Recession May Worsen This </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The recession of the Thai
economy could go from had to worse this year as the agricultural
sector, which has helped prop up entire economy, might suffer a
severe drought, Senate Speaker Meechai Ruchuphan said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Shortages of rainfall would cause farm output to drop sharply,
meaning a significant reduction in the country's earnings while
farmers' purchasing power would also weaken, Meechai was quoted
Sunday by the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
The stronger baht and a cut in the Generalized System of
Preferences for some Thai products by the European Union would
also greatly affect exports, he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover enforcement of laws on foreclosure and bankruptcy
would make many more firms collapse and cause non-performing loans
to swell, Meechai said.
</P>
<P>
He said the people could expect a rise in crime rates and
social problems this year.
</P>
<P>
Meechai, however, said he now saw tourism as a "savior" and
suggested that the government inject one or two billion baht into
the industry for promotion campaigns and development of tourist
attractions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
