<HEADLINE> U.S. Says American Aboard Plane Downed in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Saturday that at least one American was aboard a U.N.-chartered
aircraft that went down in Angola.
</P>
<P>
"The United States is shocked and saddened by the loss of a
second United Nations Observer Mission in Angola (MONUA) plane in
one week," said acting spokesman Lee McClenny of the U.S. State
Department.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft reportedly was downed over UNITA-held territory
with eight passengers and crew. This is the second such incident
in one week.
</P>
<P>
Angolan state radio said the plane was hit near Bailundo, a
UNITA stronghold some 80 km (50 miles) north of Huambo. "The
aircraft... tried in vain to make an emergency landing at Huambo
airport," it said.
</P>
<P>
On December 26, a U.N.-chartered C-130 transport plane with 14
people aboard was reportedly shot down near the same city. The
fate of its crew and passengers is unknown.
</P>
<P>
"While the final passenger list is not confirmed, we are aware
of at least one American citizen aboard. The fate of the passeng
ers and crew is uncertain, since the crash site has not yet been
reached," McClenny said.
</P>
<P>
"The United States insists that UNITA provide immediate, full
cooperation with MONUA in the face of this latest air disaster,"
McClenny said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Angolan government had given assurances of
its willingness to provide assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
