<HEADLINE> Annan "Outraged" by Downing of Second U.N. Plane in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 2 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said late on Saturday that he "is outraged by reports
of a second United Nations aircraft apparently shot down in
Angola within the past week."
</P>
<P>
Annan said in a statement that he "expects the Government of
Angola to honor its pledge to provide all possible assistance in
the efforts to rescue survivors. Furthermore, the
Secretary-General demands that UNITA cooperate without delay in
the search-and-rescue missions."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said that he urges, in the strongest possible
terms, the Angolan Government and the rebel National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) achieve "an immediate
ceasefire which will permit the conduct of search-and-rescue
missions as well as the relocation of United Nations staff to
safer areas."
</P>
<P>
"All threats to United Nations personnel -- in the air and on
the ground -- must cease immediately," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There can be no excuse for any delay on any side in
disclosing all relevant information about the fate of the
passengers and crews of the two United Nations aircraft," he
added.
</P>
<P>
In the Angolan capital of Luanda, the United Nations Observer
Mission in Angola (MONUA) said on Saturday that a U.N.-chartered
C-130 transport plane, which belongs to the South African
TransAfrik company, with eight passengers and crew aboard, was
shot down 20 minutes after taking off from Huambo airport in the
UNITA-held territory, central Angola.
</P>
<P>
Initial reports said that the aircraft carried one American,
four Angolans, two Filipinos and a Namibian. Their names were
still unknown at the moment.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Amadou Toure said in Luanda that the aircraft
had been evacuating U.N. personnel out of Huambo to Luanda
despite fierce fighting in the area.
</P>
<P>
Angolan state radio said the plane was hit near Bailundo, a
UNITA stronghold some 80 kilometers north of Huambo after the
pilot tried in vain to make an emergency landing at Huambo
airport. However, there was no immediate comment from UNITA.
</P>
<P>
On December 26, 1998, another U.N.-chartered cargo plane C-130
from TransAfrik, with 10 passengers and 4 crew members aboard,
crashed in the same area, scene of fierce fighting between
Angola's two conflicting parties.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan Government claims that UNITA is holding survivors
from the crash, but UNITA denies this and the United Nations
could not confirm the report.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council, at the request of the Russian
Mission to the United Nations, held an emergency meeting on
Thursday to condemn "the incomprehensible lack of cooperation
clarifying the circumstances of this tragedy." The 15-member
Council said it would assess the situation in Angola on January
11.
</P>
<P>
At present, the United Nations has a 1,000-member peacekeeping
contingent in Angola to monitor 1994 peace accords, shattered by
the on-going fierce fighting in central Angola, which has long
been at war since its independence from Portugal in 1975. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
