<HEADLINE> Mercosur Countries To Import Wheat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The South American
Common Market (Mercosur) countries will have to import 800,000
tons of wheat this year because of a predicted reduction of
grain production, the Brazilian newspaper Estado de Sao Paulo
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted data from the National Brazilian Staples
Company (Conab) as saying that the total 1998-1999 harvest of the
four Mercosur countries (Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay)
will be 13.3 million tons, which means a 25.3 percent drop from
the previous harvest of 17.8 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Argentina, the major wheat producer in the region, will have a
dramatic grain production reduction of 31.3 percent, from 14.7
million tons to 10.1 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The total demand of the four countries is 14.1 million tons of
wheat, of which 8.6 million tons is required by Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's grain production decreased by 8.2 percent from the
last harvest of 2.18 million tons. The country will have to
import more than 6 million tons for its domestic market this
year.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur is the largest commercial trade bloc in South
America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
