<HEADLINE> Overseas Partners Help Expand China's Offshore Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Cooperation with overseas
partners has enabled China's offshore oil production to grow over
200 times in the past 15 years, the "Business Weekly" reported on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the China National Offshore Oil Corporation (CNOOC),
the country's leading offshore oil developer, extracted 16.28
million tons of oil and 4.05 billion cubic meters of natural gas
in Chinese waters.
</P>
<P>
Taking account of the oil production of CNOOC's overseas
shares, its total annual production amounted to 20.33 million tons
of oil equivalent, more than 200 times that of 1982, when China's
offshore crude oil production was less than 100,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
CNOOC President Wei Liucheng attributed its expansion to
cooperation with overseas partners.
</P>
<P>
To date, the CNOOC has signed 137 petroleum contracts and
agreements with 68 overseas oil companies from 18 countries and
regions for oil exploration and development.
</P>
<P>
So far, it has attracted at least seven billion U.S. dollars of
overseas capital, of which more than three billion has been used
for exploration, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The CNOOC is now implementing 41 oil contracts and agreements
with 37 foreign companies, including Chevron, Texaco, Phillips,
Arco and Amoco, Cao Yunshi, manager of CNOOC's contracts and
regulations departments.
</P>
<P>
In February 1998, CNOOC and Royal Dutch Shell officially
announced to jointly build the world-class Nanhai petrochemical
project in the Guangdong city of Huizhou.
</P>
<P>
With a total contracted investment of around 4.5 billion
U.S. dollars, the joint venture is China's largest Sino-foreign
cooperative project.
</P>
<P>
Following the progress of offshore cooperation, China also
opened 11 southern provinces and autonomous regions to foreign oil
explorers and developers in 1985. In 1992, another 10 northern
provinces and regions were opened.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
