<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Make All-Out efforts to Promote Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
an unnamed high-profile official is quoted as saying that
export rebate rates on machinery and electronics products and some
othe internationally marketable products will be raised to help
improve the competitiveness of Chinese exports.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Chinese exporters will enjoy more policy support
that will enable them to have better access to export credit,
export credit insurance and guarantee policies.
</P>
<P>
Starting from January 1, the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) began to grant import and export
authority to more Chinese firms, especially privately-owned
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
China will also encourage its firms to start processing
industries overseas with their self-supplied equipment and raw
materials as a way to expand exports.
</P>
<P>
"Transferring some surplus processing industries to countries
who need them, especially in Latin America and Africa, will be
beneficial to both China and those nations," Sun Weiyan, president
of the University of International Business and Economics in
Beijing, said earlier in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
It will help China expand exports on one hand, and help those
nations to develop processing industries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hard hit by the Asian financial turmoil, China's exports is
predicted to reach a zero or negative growth in 1998. The export
volume in the first 11 months of 1998 inched up 0.2 percent from
the same period a year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
