<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based Newspapers  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- This Chinese capital of Beijing has done practical and
effective work in helping more laid-off workers find new jobs last
year by the means of adding training courses, improving social
security network and expanding communal services. It has so far
set up some 340 job agencies and the reemployment rate of laid-off
workers for January to November was 57.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chongqing, the country's youngest municipality as
well as the largest industrial center in southwest China, has
established 1,998 reemployment service centers in state-owned
enterprises. Last year, 143,000 workers laid off from the city's
state- and collectively-owned enterprises found reemployment.
</P>
<P>
-- In an accompanying editor's note, the newspaper called for
careful implementation of the Party and the State Council's
policies on doing a good job of ensuring basic life of laid-offs
from the state-owned enterprises and helping them find new jobs,
and urged localities to be more conscientious, zealous and
responsible in properly arranging the laid-offs.
</P>
<P>
-- Shanghai metropolis in east China fulfilled 81.43 billion
yuan (9.8 billion US dollars) in revenues in 1998, a rise of 11
percent over the 1997, of which, local revenues made up 39.22
billion yuan. It levied 91.93 billion yuan (11 billion US dollars)
in industrial and commercial taxes in the past year, up 9.2
percent over the previous year.
</P>
</TEXT>
