<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina Reaffirms Sovereignty Over Malvinas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Argentine government
reaffirmed on Saturday that it would work to resume its
sovereignty over the Malvinas Islands through diplomatic
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
A communique distributed by the foreign ministry said that "on
the 166th anniversary of the illegal occupation of the Malvinas
by the British, the Argentine people and government reaffirm
their sovereignty over these islands."
</P>
<P>
The communique recalled that the Malvinas Islands were
occupied by British forces on January 3,1833 after expelling
local inhabitants and the Argentine authorities.
</P>
<P>
While emphasizing its sovereignty over the Malvinas, Argentina
will continue exploring understanding of the United Kingdom to
build mutual confidence and promote cooperation in the Southern
Atlantic, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
Argentina and Britain have had a long-standing dispute over
the sovereignty of the Malvinas, known as the Falkland Islands to
the British, which culminated in a 74-day war in April 1982.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
