<DOCNO> XIE19990103.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urged to Invest More in Farm Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The capabilities of research and
development (R&AMP;D) in the agriculture sector will largely determine
how well can China deal with food security problems in the next
millennium, according to China Daily today.
</P>
<P>
It's predicted that by the the year 2030, China will produce
more than 1.5 times the current grain volume to feed a population
of 1.6 billion people, while the demand for livestock and aquatic
products will double.
</P>
<P>
This means that the real grain demand will hit 640 million tons
with a per capita rate of 400 kg by then. The output growth per
hectare should reach 1.4 percent annually, jumping 60 percent from
the current basis, if China attempts to meet all its food needs
domestically.
</P>
<P>
"The application of advanced technologies will play a central
role in sustaining grain output growth at the time, given China's
limited land resources and the world's largest population," said
Huang Yikun, director with Center for Chinese Agricultural Policy
(CCAP).
</P>
<P>
Huang said the government should take effective measures to
bolster the current unsatisfactory levels R&AMP;D progress in the
agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
But, Huang noted, China's investment ratio in agricultural
research is less than half the developed world's average in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from CCAP, China's agricultural
research investment accounted for only 0.36 percent of the gross
domestic product (GDP) in 1996, lagging 0.29 percent behind that
of the world's 30 poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
However, China has to feed 22 percent of the world's population
with seven percent of the world's total arable land.
</P>
<P>
"Under current growth pace, it will take us 45 years to keep up
with middle income countries in terms of agricultural development
investment," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
The CCAP statistics indicates that the government's financial
allocations for agricultural research had an average negative
growth of 0.8 percent in the 1985-96 period.
</P>
<P>
At present, many research items are designated by government
departments, ignoring feasibility and market demand, China Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the research results cannot maintain sustained
development since the whole process is divided by different
administration, the newspaper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
