<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renminbi to Remain Stable, Safe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese currency Renminbi (RMB)
will remain stable in the last two years of the century whereas
the status of the currency will be consolidated and assume
increasing importance as a stabilizing force in world financial
systems.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily quoted economist Li Guobin, a noted
economist from the State Information Center saying that RMB assets
will remain minimum risk and maximum yields during 1999 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the actual interest rate of RMB at present is
already two percentage points higher than that of US dollars and
major European currencies, which has resulted in high yields for
RMB assets. Even if the central bank cut the interest rate by one
percentage point in the next two years, he added, the actual
interest rate for RMB could still remain between 3.3 to 2.27
percent.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the state foreign exchange reserves will
remain higher than 145 billion US dollars. Counting 110 billion of
foreign exchange assets shared by individuals, enterprises and
financial institutions, China has foreign exchange reserves of
about 250 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, China will see annual demands for
foreign exchange amounting to 60 billion US dollars, including 20
billion US dollars for foreign debt repayment and 30 billion for
three-month imports payments.
</P>
<P>
Li further predicts that the State foreign exchange reserves
and the supply capacity for hard currency will keep growing in the
next two years, as China is expected to maintain the favorable
balance of international payments.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, sustained economic growth in China will
enhance the international appeal of RMB assets because of higher
yields.
</P>
<P>
According to Li, China can keep its economic growth around
eight percent in 1999 and 2000 while the world economic growth can
only maintain 1.2 percent growth this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
