<HEADLINE> Foreign Capital Flees Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Five billion U.S.
dollars of foreign capital fled Brazil in December, the biggest
loss since September, due to the international financial
turmoil, the Brazilian newspaper O Estado de Sao Paulo reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
 The country's total exchange flow in the month had a 5.19
billion dollar loss, as the remittances of resources surpassed
the income by 1.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
 The country's foreign exchange reserves dropped from 67.33
billion dollars to 38 billion dollars, as about 30 billion
dollars left the country between August and December of 1998.
</P>
<P>
 The Brazilian currency devalued by 8.37 percent from
1.1164 reals per dollar at the end of 1997 to 1.2087 reals in
December of 1998, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
