<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Launch of Euro a Mixed Blessing for China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The launch of the euro is a
mixed blessing for China's foreign trade and foreign direct
investment inflows, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
On the whole, Chinese firms will benefit from a huge market in
one currency, rather than 11 fragmented markets, which makes it
easier to penetrate, according to Michael Oliver of the Hong Kong
Branch of Germany's Commerzbank AG.
</P>
<P>
This will reduce exchange risks and trading costs in trade
between China and the euro-zone, and hence meaning bigger profit
margins for Chinese firms, said Wang Yuanlong, a researcher with
the Institute of International Finance.
</P>
<P>
Faster EU economic growth prompted by the adoption of a single
currency will mean larger demands for products outside the
European Union, said Zhou Wenming, a researcher with the Chinese
Academy of International Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, Zhu Min, director of the Bank of China's Institute
of International Finance, warned that Chinese firms will have to
reposition themselves in the European market, as European banks
and big companies will experience consolidation and restructuring
to adjust to the new market environment.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Chinese firms will face strong competition from East
and South European countries, which also offer low-priced
labor-intensive products, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Price transparency will also set spurs to trading within the
euro zone, lead to lower prices and hence lower profit margins,
and force European companies to be more efficient. All these will
make market competition more fierce for Chinese firms.
</P>
<P>
It will also put an end to the strategy of differential
pricing, which is usually employed by Chinese firms in trade with
European countries to achieve maximum benefits, Zhou said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990103.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Launch of Euro a Mixed Blessing for China  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In addition, Zhou noted, Chinese firms will have to shoulder
mounting currency conversion costs incurred by the launch of
euro. They have to resolve the technical aspects of trade
settlements and valuations, training their employees, employing
new computer software and preparing new sets of financial
statements.
</P>
<P>
In the short term, there are also exchange rate risks, the
researchers said.
</P>
<P>
The euro is expected to be strong in the long run, considering
the economic strength of the 11 countries. However, the short-term
adjustment after the debut of the euro also means exchange rate
risks, according to China Daily.
</P>
<P>
This is especially so during the transitional period from 1991
to 2001, Zhou added.
</P>
<P>
As for the impact of the euro on China's foreign direct
investment inflows, the researchers agreed that it will to some
extent divert some foreign direct investment from China. The
reduced investment costs in the EU resulting from a single
European currency are expected to attract more international
investment. Meanwhile, the EU's integration efforts also encourage
investment from developed EU countries to backward ones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990103.0137 </DOCNO>
