<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Central Bank to Include Euro in Exchange Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Venezuela
(BCV) will change part of its foreign exchange reserves
denominated in dollars for the new unified European currency, the
euro, Antonio Casas Gonzalez, president of Venezuela's money
issuing institute, has said.
</P>
<P>
"We are studying the percentage of euros we will introduce
into the reserves. It is an important alternate to the dollar,"
Casas was quoted as saying Saturday by "El Universal," the only
newspaper that circulates via Internet in Venezuela during the
holidays.
</P>
<P>
Casas said the new currency has many advantages for Europe and
that it will make commercial transactions more agile and less
costly.
</P>
<P>
The BCV president said the bank will include the euro as a
reserve currency since it is considered more important than the
Japanese yen and that it is almost at the same level as the U.S.
dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
