<HEADLINE> Ethiopians Take Men's and Women's Events </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Milion Wolde and Gete Wami gave
Ethiopia a double triumph in the International Amateur Athletic
Federation World Cross Challenge series, winning the men's and
women's races in Durham, England on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Wami, the 1996 World cross country champion, ran away from her
rivals in the second half of the women's 6.5 km race, crossing
the line in 21 minutes 58 seconds, 13 seconds clear of
second-placed Jackline Maranga of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Finland's Annemari Sandell was third while European champion
Paula Radcliffe of Britain, still recovering from the
after-effects of a cold, managed only fourth place.
</P>
<P>
Wami, who won the opening race in the series two weeks ago in
Belgium, leads rankings with 50 points with Sandell second on 41.
</P>
<P>
Wolde, the reigning world junior cross country champion, had a
tougher time as he won the men's 9 km race.
</P>
<P>
John Kosgei made all the early running and led into the last
of seven laps but then the Kenyan ran out of steam leaving the
race to be decided between Wolde, Kenya's Thomas Nyariki and
Britain's Jon Brown.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian proved the quicker in the three-man sprint for
the line, finishing in 27:02.
</P>
<P>
Nyariki finished second, just two seconds adrift, but moved to
the top of the rankings with 39 points.
</P>
<P>
Brown, the 1996 European cross country champion, had to be
content with third place in 27:05. 
</P>
</TEXT>
