<HEADLINE> Leukaemia Could Be Inherited: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- British scientists, by
pinpointing a gene responsible for some cases of the most common
type of leukaemia, have found the first evidence of a hereditary
link to the disease.
</P>
<P>
The discovery, published Saturday in The Lancet medical
journal, showed that almost 20 percent of sufferers of chronic
lymphocytic leukaemia (CLL) could have a mutated version of the
gene known as ATM.
</P>
<P>
Of these, one in three may have inherited the fault, reported
Professor Malcolm Taylor and colleagues from Birmingham
University.
</P>
<P>
"We have suspected for some time that a number of patients with
this type of leukaemia could be carriers of a faulty gene."
Professor Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
"But the fact that we have been able to isolate the specific
gene and show that it could run in families is certainly a major
scientific step forward," he said.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the discovery should help scientists develop
new ways to repair the defective gene and ultimately prevent CLL
developing.
</P>
<P>
CLL, the most common type of leukaemia affecting people over 50
in 90 percent of cases, is not immediately life-threatening and
its progression can be effectively controlled by drugs for many
years.
</P>
<P>
Its main danger is in weakening the patients' immune system and
leaving sufferers susceptible to other serious infections.
</P>
<P>
Professor Taylor's team believe, however, that problems with
the ATM gene could be responsible for a more aggressive form of
the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
