<DOCNO> XIE19990103.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Personal Stereos Can Damage Hearing, Study Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Personal stereos can seriously
damage the hearing of people who have suffered middle ear
infections as children, French researchers have found.
</P>
<P>
The investigators assessed hearing status in 1,208 young men
aged 18-24 years who were having medical examinations at selection
centers for the army in France.
</P>
<P>
Writing in the medical journal The Lancet, the researchers from
the Centre de Recherche du Service de Sante de Armees at La
Tonche, said that the use of personal stereos for at least one
hour a day was found to harm the youngsters' hearing.
</P>
<P>
Approximately one in five of those youngsters who used personal
stereos with the volume turned up high experienced problems with
their hearing.
</P>
<P>
The level of noise at which they could detect a sound was much
higher than those with normal hearing. The phenomenon was found
for sounds at all normal human hearing frequency range.
</P>
<P>
The harmful effect, however, was strongly dependent on whether
the men had suffered repeated middle-ear infections in infancy or
in childhood.
</P>
<P>
Personal stereos had no effect on men without a history of ear
infections. For those who had suffered childhood ear infections
the loudness threshold at which they could hear sounds was on
average 11 decibels higher than normal.
</P>
<P>
"Young people with a history of repeated episodes of otitis
media should be warned that personal stereo use is a risk factor
for deafness." the researchers suggested. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
